[5] Argentina
Date: Fri 24 Apr 2009
Source: El Financiero [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod. TY, edited]
<http://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/ElFinanciero/Portal/cfpages/contentmgr.cfm?docId=185600&docTipo=1&orderby=docid&sortby=ASC>


The political and health crisis unleashed in Argentina by the
epidemic of dengue worsened today [24 Apr 2009] after the
organization Doctors Without Flags [Medicos sin Banderas in Spanish,
an Argentina-based non-governmental organization of physicians. -
Mod.TY] reported that there are 100 000 cases in the country, instead
of the 23 thousand estimated by the government.

"There are infected individuals who have no severe symptoms and many
others who have not come to the hospital because they self-medicate,
[therefore] official notifications are not realistic," said Ariel
Umpierrez, member of the organization. He added that there is much
concern and alarm because the northern provinces of the country face
a serious risk by the proliferation of dengue cases.

Umpierrez indicated that Doctors Without Flags calculated number of
patients in accordance with standards established the World Health
Organization (WHO) in facing any epidemic. He explained that the 1st
recommendation is to multiply by 5 the official [number of] cases,
which would exceed even the 100 000 infected individuals that this
organization considers there are already in the entire country.

The official estimates are incorrect, stressed Umpierrez, because
there are people who identify the symptoms as dengue and they know
they can fight it with paracetamol [acetaminophen], so they stay in
their homes.

"We're not saying that the national Ministry of Health Nation is
giving false figures. We are only warning that they are unrealistic;
laboratory confirmation is not the only reality," he said.

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Quantification of the actual number of dengue virus infections given
the wide spectrum of clinical severity over a large geographic area,
in the face of an outbreak, is always challenging. Intensive,
prospective studies that capture mild cases that do not enter the
health care system, invariably lead to an under-estimation of the
numbers of total infections. Capturing these milder case numbers
requires labor-intensive, and very costly household-level surveillance.

A map showing the location of the provinces in Argentina ca be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/argentina_pol96.jpg>.
A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Argentina can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/r/008K>. - Mod.TY]

