[6] Sri Lanka (Southern Province)
Date: Wed 29 Apr 2009
Source: Daily Mirror [edited]
<http://www.dailymirror.lk/DM_BLOG/Sections/frmNewsDetailView.aspx?ARTID=47438>


The dreaded dengue fever, which has killed 6 people and affected
hundreds so far this year [2009] is fast spreading in the Southern
Province compelling educational authorities to close down 7 schools
in the province, Health Services Director Dr JB Senarath said. He
said the cases reported indicated a 2-fold increase when compared
with the same period last year [2008].

Dr Senarath said that during the 1st 4 months this year [2009] there
were 137 cases of dengue reported from Matara and 65 from Galle,
while 6 of the effected had died. Doctors said in addition to the
usual symptoms of dengue fever the patients undergoing treatment at
hospitals in the South also showed signs of swelling of the liver and
the bloating of the abdomen causing them to question whether the
patients were suffering from dengue or some other disease.

Blood samples have been sent to Colombo for detailed examination.
Tangalle Medical Officer, Dr C Amarasinghe, had also said that
victims who are suspected to have died dengue had shown symptoms that
were different to those suffering from dengue. She said 15 such
patients were being treated at Matara and Karapitiya hospitals.

Zonal Education Director, SH Sunil, said the fast spreading dengue
fever had compelled the authorities to close until further notice the
Tangalle Balika MV; Tangalle boys National School; Tangalle Primary
School; Tangalle Model Primary School; Rahula MV; Polonnaruwa Junior
Vidyalaya, and Muslim Junior School.

He said several awareness programmes were conducted for school
principals and school children and despite the closure of schools
cleaning programmes would continue. Mr Sunil said the schools would
be reopened after health officials confirm that the situation had
returned to normal.

He said parents' ignorance as to the gravity of the problem had
aggravated the situation.

[Byline: Ariyadasa Kankanamge, Swarna Nettikumbura]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett

[The occurrence of symptoms not characteristic of dengue virus
infection mentioned in this report require a comprehensive laboratory
diagnosis to determine the etiology of the observed illness. ProMED
will be interested in finding out what the results of the laboratory
tests are, when they become available.

