[7] Saudi Arabia
Date: Sun 3 May 2009
Source: The National [edited]
<http://www.thenational.ae/article/20090504/FOREIGN/705039824/1011/NEWS>


Municipal authorities in Mecca, Jeddah, and Taif are struggling to
control an outbreak of dengue fever in the cities, to the extent that
the World Health Organisation last month [April 2009] sent a
delegation to assess the situation.

While authorities have declined to comment on the outcome of the WHO
visit, various officials have given different figures for the number
of people who have contracted the disease, as well as different
accounts of the seriousness of the outbreak.

The mayor of Jeddah, Adil Faqeeh, told reporters in March [2009] the
number of people afflicted by dengue fever in his city had risen to
104 that month from 84 in February.

In the city of Mecca, the non-governmental National Society for Human
Rights (NSHR) reported last month [April 2009] that nearly 150 people
had been hospitalised with dengue fever in the past 3 months. Press
reports said the number of cases is rising and the disease has spread
to the city of Taif which, along with Jeddah and Mecca, is located in
Mecca [Makkah] province.

Moreover, the daily Okaz reported 2 weeks ago that Mr Faqeeh had
secretly reopened the municipality's crisis management unit, which
had been closed 2 years ago, last month.

However, the Saudi health minister, Dr Abdullah al Rabeeah, told a
press conference on 25 Apr [2009] that only 44 cases of dengue fever
have been reported in total since the outbreak of the disease in
December [2008]. "The ministry of health does not deny the presence
of the fever in [Mecca] province but it is at a very low rate
compared to other parts of the world. Serious efforts are under way
to contain its spread in the region" [he said].

Dr al Rabeeah also denied press reports there had been deaths as a
result of the disease in Mecca province. Okaz reported 2 weeks ago
that a man and a woman, both in their 20s, had died in hospital and
quoted the father of the man as saying dengue fever had been the
cause of his son's death.

According to Mr Faqeeh, the outbreak in Jeddah is concentrated in the
city's slums, where poor sanitation facilities, unclean water, and
the city's still incomplete sewage system all facilitate the spread
of the disease. Sewage in Jeddah is collected in a lake called the
"musk lake," which is a breeding ground for the mosquitoes that
transmit the disease [virus] and is located close to slum areas.

Mr Faqeeh launched an awareness campaign in March [2009] against
dengue fever. The government has spent an estimated 1.4 billion
riyals (United Arab Emirates dirham 1.37 billion) [about USD 373.3
million] on combating the disease, though it is unclear what the
funds have been spent on.

[Byline: Wael Mahdi]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett

[There is a discrepancy between the numbers of dengue cases over the
past 3 months reported by the National Society for Human Rights (150
hospitalized cases) and those reported by the Ministry of Health (44
total cases). It would be of interest to know how many of these
reported cases are laboratory confirmed. Household water catchments,
rather than the sewage lagoon, are breeding sites of the _Aedes
aegypti_ mosquito vector of dengue virus, so that is where vector
control efforts should be focused.

The province of Makkah (Mecca) can be located on the map of Saudi Arabia at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/saudi_arabia_pol_2003.pdf>.
A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Saudi Arabia can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/r/00aE>. - Mod.TY]
